Monday August 19th 2013 11:16 am -04:00,There are several reasons for doing it that way. But one of the main reasons as has been already suggested has to do with memory allocation.But think of it this way. Imagine that you have 10 different variables i.e. a b c d etc. And they all contain the exact same number 2. Which is more efficient? Using 10 separate locations in memory to store 10 copies of the exact same number 2. Or using just one memory location to store the number 2 and have the variables point to that location instead., Approved Resolved,12
Monday August 19th 2013 12:38 pm -04:00,I dont think its unique to Python. Im pretty sure there are other languages out there that use the same method.But I do know that a fair amount of other languages dont do it that way at all. Which is why it does cause some confusion when certain programmers are coming from another language. Theyre still thinking that each variable is like a totally separate box that you put stuff in. But of course its not like that at all.For example once you start making one variable being equal to another variable strange things start to happen. You change one variable and the other variable may or may not change as well all depending on the data type i.e. if the object is mutable or immutable. That sort of thing can be confusing but its not that confusing., Approved Resolved,2
Tuesday August 20th 2013 2:43 am -04:00,Theres always a lot of confusion when it comes to Python and its data typing mainly due to the exact nature of what weve just been discussing i.e. variables pointing to values. But Python is not a loosely or weakly-typed language its actually a strongly-typed language.So for example a string in Python is a string and an integer is an integer. You cant add different data types together like you would in JavaScript for example. Thats the difference between a strongly-typed and weakly-typed language.Python is also a dynamically-typed language as opposed to statically-typed. Amongst other things this refers to the variables themselves. It makes sense that Python is considered as dynamically-typed since any variable could be pointing to an integer in one line of code and the exact same variable be pointing to a string in the next. Thats the difference between dynamically-typed and statically-typed.And as Ivan mentioned in Python it`s not really a good idea to state data types in variable names. Unless it`s for educational purposes and so on. But you can actually see what one of the reasons would be for not using such names from my example above in that a variable could be pointing to an integer in one instance and then suddenly be pointing to a string in the next line of code. Hence the variable name `intAge` could actually be misleading in that it`s now a string., Approved Resolved,5
