Tuesday August 27th 2013 1:52 am -04:00,One thing to keep in mind in terms of functions is that something will ALWAYS be returned. Its not a question of whats the difference between print and return. Something will always be returned regardless if you print to the console or not.A function is like a blackbox. You may not know its inner workings. Or how exactly it does its stuff. Or even care. But if you put something into a function well guess what something will ALWAYS come out.Now you may not actually notice it in Python that something is being returned but if you dont specify a return statement then a so-called hidden return statement will be inserted for you. And that so-called return is called None. Which is basically equivalent to nothing but its still something.So the following two functions are exactly the same thing: >>> def f(x):	print(x * 2)>>> def f(x):	print(x * 2)	return None  Check out this code to see whats happening... >>> print(f(5))10None>>> x = f(5)10>>> type(x)<class NoneType> Notice in the first example that the function does its thing prints 10 but then returns None even though there was no return statement. You only notice that None was returned if you actually print it out to the console.So dont get confused with what a function actually does. It can print to the console update a variable turn your screen blue or whatever. But it will always return something. Either you can specify it explicitly in terms of what a function will return. Or if not then Python will actually do it for you implicitly by returning None.,None,4
