Wednesday August 28th 2013 10:15 am -04:00,Theres an easy way to think about modulo and thats to use the clock system. Its used fairly often in games etc. such as rock-paper-scissors when you dont want to write a whole bunch of complex code in terms of who beat who. So you simply represent everything onto a clock and move clockwise or counter-clockwise from the top.For example -1 % 24 is very easy. Thats a 24-hour clock move counter-clockwise by 1 since its negative 1 and where does the dial-hand point to? 23 obviously.How about  3 % 24? Again move clockwise this time because 3 is positive and the dial-hand ends up at 3. Both these examples are known as positive clocks because the 24 is positive.A little more complicated but still the same principle are negative clocks. For example 3 % -24 is considered a negative clock because 24 is negative. Which means we do the opposite of clockwise and counter-clockwise. So in this example we move counter-clockwise by 3 and end up at 21 but its a negative 21 because its a negative clock.Hope its not too confusing but once you understand the clock system its very easy.P.S. Lets try the -134 % 24 that was mentioned above. Thats a positive clock which means we move counter-clockwise 134 times. Which is equivalent to 5 complete rotations and 14 left over. Or -14 % 24. So move counter-clockwise 14 times and where does the dial-hand point to? 10 obviously., Resolved,3
Wednesday August 28th 2013 10:26 am -04:00,Heres another example to try out using the clock system. Two negative numbers! :)-3 % -24Is that a positive or negative clock? And which way do we go? Clockwise or counter-clockwise?, Resolved,1
