Wednesday August 28th 2013 8:40 am -04:00,Another interesting aspect is how Python will store variables and their values. This was mentioned in another thread by Professor Paul Gries and is considered advanced stuff for now.But Python will convert the names of variables into strings in order to store them in a dictionary. Dont worry if you dont know about dictionaries yet itll be covered later on in the course. Its just a Key:Value pair like a real dictionary. The Key is the variable and the Value is the value of the variable.Notice below how variables are stored. Theyre all strings. Notice int and float remain the same. Double-quotes get turned into single-quotes except if you use both of them. And Unicode characters are actually characters but that may depend on your system.So yes technically variables are strings. :-)  >>> my_variable_1 = 2.3456>>> my_variable_2 = 23456>>> my_variable_3 = this is a string>>> my_variable_4 = \u65e6>>> my_variable_5 = this is Daves string>>> locals(){__name__: __main__ __builtins__: <module builtins> my_variable_2: 23456 my_variable_3: this is a string __doc__: None __package__: None __loader__: <class _frozen_importlib.BuiltinImporter> my_variable_1: 2.3456 my_variable_4: 旦 my_variable_5: this is Daves string}, Resolved,1
