Wednesday September 4th 2013 2:57 am -04:00,The terminal is a very basic way to interact with your computer. You can use the terminal to run Python or any other program for that matter. But basically all you can do with a terminal is to type in commands. Theres no menu bar graphics you cant use your mouse or anything like that. Anyways thats what a terminal is suppose to be just like it was in the 1950s. But a modern day terminal is now just a pop-up window that tries to look and act like a terminal i.e. a so-called terminal emulator.IDLE though is just for Python. You cant type commands to run a spreadsheet for example. Its also a GUI (graphical user interface) that makes it easier to interact with your computer in that it has a menu bar you can use your mouse etc. You can type in the same sort of commands as a terminal if youre running Python but it also has many other features. IDLE is also called an IDE (Integrated Development Environment) in that it doesnt just run code but can also debug your code run tests etc.As to why you have two different versions of Python i.e. 2.6.1 and 3.3.2 thats probably because your Apple operating system came with a pre-installed version of Python. And when you launch the terminal it points to the 2.6.1 version. No doubt you must have installed Python 3 on your system as well? So no doubt IDLE is configured that run that version. Im not an Apple user but you could probably configure the terminal to use Python 3 as well if you really wanted to.But as you probably know for this course were using Python 3 which does have some differences from version 2.,None,0
