Wednesday September 4th 2013 4:40 pm -04:00,Theres no problem with the lecture summary its just fine. The only thing wrong is the typo which Etienne mentioned in that one decimal points should be one decimal point without the s.When it refers to one decimal point it literally means just one decimal point and NOT the number of digits to the right of the decimal point. So float (-43.21) is perfectly valid. And so is float (-43.215)etc.Having float (-43.2.1) will generate a ValueError since it actually has more than one decimal point.Thats what is meant.As for the int function theres no mention of one decimal point two decimal point etc. because as soon as you have anything other than a digit ie. a string with a decimal point then it will generate a ValueError.And that is mentioned in the summary i.e. int(-99.9) will generate a ValueError because its not all digits.Hope this explains what is meant by decimal points., Resolved,0
Friday September 6th 2013 4:26 am -04:00,My advice would be to not try to memorize the terminology. Much better to understand the meaning instead if you ask me. Its like trying to memorize a physics formula which can be extremely hard. And youre no further ahead if you ever have to use it. Much better to understand what the formula is saying in the first place.Usually the terminology is just plain English and will immediately jump out at you if you look closely enough. Heres some basic examples and ways to think about what weve learned so far...Variables are things that vary. Again its just plain English.Arguments are constantly changing. Think of an actual argument i.e. one with your spouse or girlfriend. Everyone has a different argument and it could be anything.Expressions are things that people utter or say. In Python an expression is something that you as the programmer wont say but would type out as text instead.Expressions get evaluated just like in real life. If someone expresses a certain feeling towards me then the first thing Im going to do is try to figure out or evaluate what they just said.Evaluate is just a process that literally means what it means i.e. youll get some sort of value.Frames are exactly like picture frames. You know those square things you hang on the wall. Frames are a diagram with four lines one for each side and they have something inside.Stacks are exactly like whatever stack you can think of. In Python we stack a bunch of frames on top of one another. Thats all a stack is. If you dont believe me then just look at a picture of a call stack i.e. its just a diagram of 4-sided boxes (frames) stacked on top of each other.  So if you look closely at all this so-called terminology youll soon notice that a lot of it is just plain English. And that you probably already know the meaning of these words. And that theres usually no real need to memorize or look up anything., Resolved,2
