Friday September 6th 2013 11:49 am -04:00,Just wanted to mention that the problem wasnt the get_hours function calling itself. Youre actually allowed to do that believe it or not. Not sure if were going to learn that technique later on but a function calling itself is known as recursion. So you could have something like this:  def get_hours(seconds):    # body of code here    return get_hours(seconds)  The real problem is as the error message states. Theres two types and the existing code is trying to divide one type by another type. In this case were trying to divide the function itself get_hours by the integer 2. Point to note is that theres no parentheses after get_hours so its not a call to the function but really the function itself.So logically dividing a function by 2 just doesnt make sense hence the TypeError., Resolved,0
Friday September 6th 2013 11:11 am -04:00,Just like to mention that Whitmans error message is really great in terms of learning how to read errors..  TypeError: unsupported operand type(s) for //: function and int  First its a TypeError which means theres some sort of conflict between one or more types i.e. a string an integer etc. In this case the conflict is between a function and an int the two so-called operands.Second we have operands but whats the operator you know the symbol that separates the two? In this case the error message says the operator is // which is the integer division symbol.So when we think about it we dont even really need to look at the code to figure out whats wrong. This is a case of trying to divide a function by an integer. Not the results of a function divided by an integer. But trying to divide the actual function itself. Now obviously that doesnt make any sense hence the error message.All very interesting. :-), Resolved,0
