Friday September 6th 2013 2:21 pm -04:00,Mastering a language would be quite a feat and an accomplishment thats for sure. I dont think anyone has truly mastered a language? Okay maybe a select few but these are the elite programmers. No doubt though they are still learning new things everyday.In terms of going from Python to another language I would say anyone who finishes this course and follows-up with some object-oriented programming (OOP) could easily learn another language very quickly. Its always the concepts that are the hardest to learn not the syntax of a language.In fact I would even say that you could look at a C# program for example or JavaScript without any prior experience. And actually understand whats going on. It would just be a matter of understanding the syntax but the functions would be the same. And if you know OOP then you would immediately recognize the various classes methods etc. and how everything is put together.In terms of learning more than one language I think theres two schools of thought out there...First school of thought says to learn a bit of one language and get exposed to many other languages that will in turn help you develop a greater understanding of what you already know. This can be quite time consuming but the idea is that the sum is greater than the parts. You may not know everything but youve mastered the basics.Second school of thought says to focus on one language only. Pick a horse and stick with it. The benefit of focus is that youll be able to move beyond the basics and get into higher-level concepts that you would not normally have time for if you had tried to learn other languages as well. Knowing quite a lot and being fairly proficient is a plus. But the downside would be the lack of a greater understanding that comes from those other languages.I know for me personally I still havent figured it out. Everything is still a constant battle LOL.,None,2
