Monday September 9th 2013 2:42 pm -04:00,Vijay I have a great example for you that relates specifically to the mathematical thinking course that youre doing. Not sure if youve learned how to work with implications yet?But youre going to love this. You were wondering if programming could actually help me learn Math. So lets use some programming and Python itself to do some mathematical thinking.Here we go...Implication is about if/then statements i.e. p implies q or p => q or not(p) or q using logical operators. In plain English its implied that if I learn programming then Ill learn mathematics. So if its True thatI learned programming and its True that I learned mathematics then the implication is True i.e. p => q  is True. In Python it looks like this...  >>> p q = True True>>> not(p) or qTrue If its True that I learned programming and its False that I learned mathematics then the implication is False i.e. p => q  is False. Which makes sense...  >>> p q = True False>>> not(p) or qFalse  If its False that I learned programming and its True that I learned mathematics then the implication is True i.e. p => q  is True. This one is harder to understand but it still makes sense. If I dont learn programming then Im still free to do whatever I want in terms of mathematics. It was never implied that If I didnt learn programming that I couldnt learn mathematics.  >>> p q = False True>>> not(p) or qTrue  If its False that I learned programming and its False that I learned mathematics then the implication is True i.e. p => q  is True. Last one...  >>> p q = False False>>> not(p) or qTrue  Learning Math through programming in action. :-),None,2
