Monday September 9th 2013 10:35 pm -04:00,Tim explained the recursive process and notation fairly well. But you can also just look at the code and visually step through it to figure out whats going on.As Tim mentioned the argument is an index or the position in the Fibonacci sequence. So index 0 is the first number index 1 is the second number i.e. fib(7) will return 13 which is the 8th number in the sequence.First index is easy fib(0) will hit the if statement and return 0 end of function call. Second is also easy fib(1) jumps past the if statement will hit the elif and return 1 end of function call.Third index fib(2) starts to get interesting. Itll hit the else statement and this is where recursion starts. We know n = 2 but we actually have two function calls in the else statement. No problem one gets called and does it thing then the second one gets called and does its thing. Then the returns of those two get added together and the whole thing is returned.So when n = 2 we get a function call of fib(2-1) or fib(1) which returns 1. And a function call of fib(2-2) or fib(0) which returns 0. Which in turn returns 1 + 0 which is 1. Does fib(2) or the index 2 of the Fibonacci sequence equal to 1? The answer is yes.In terms of recursion dont think about a function calling itself. Just think of it as the first function calling another function which just happens to have the exact same code.Using the Python Visualizer you can see the frames being stacked on top of each other every time the function gets called. Its very obvious when you use higher index numbers. Initially itll create a stack of frames and then work backwards returning values to the previous frame: http://pythontutor.com/visualize.html#code=def+fib(n)%3A%0A++++if+n+%3D%3D+0%3A%0A++++++++return+0%0... Notice the number of steps. As you go higher its not just an increase in steps but an exponential increase in the number of steps. Simply because you have function calls in function calls which in turn create even more function calls.The only thing you may not notice is that once a frame returns a value to the previous frame itll disappear and a new one will be created. But thats hard to tell because guess what the function calls all have the same name. :-),None,0
