Friday September 13th 2013 4:05 am -04:00,Adina defragmenting and stacks have nothing to do with each other.Defragmenting has to do with your hard drive also known as your hard disk and not with any sort of memory either. As stuff gets saved onto your hard drive it may not necessarily get saved in the same area. Think of a video that you just downloaded. There may be fragments all over your hard drive. And when the time comes to play it well your hard drive is looking all over the place for the various fragments.So what defragmentation does is try to put all the various pieces of a video or whatever sort of file into one area of the hard drive. This way itll speed up your system and the hard drive itself wont have to keep looking for stuff.Youre right about the automatic defragmenting that goes on nowadays. Before you had to defrag every so often just to keep your hard drive up to speed. Now most of that is done automatically., Resolved,0
Friday September 13th 2013 4:54 pm -04:00,Adina let me see if I can make some distinctions or try to clarify the situation since youre talking about a lot of different things.Hard drives and memory are both hardware. A hard drive is the spinning disk in your computer. Memory is made up of computer chips that are on your motherboard. The only difference between the two is that things stored on a hard drive are permanent. While things stored in a memory chip will disappear when you turn the power off.Now in terms of software. Software doesnt have memory. Software is just lines of code that are stored on your hard drive. And if you run a piece of software then some of the code will also be loaded into the memory chips since its much easier and faster to process bits of information in a memory chip than it is on a hard drive. Hard drives are very slow compared to memory chips.Now in terms of what were talking about i.e. stacks and frames. Those are just programming terms. If you create a function then a frame gets created and that frame is stored somewhere in memory i.e. it has a memory address. If you call a function then another frame gets created which also gets stored in memory. And frames get stacked on top of one another.Eventually as your program does its thing well frames will disappear one by one since each frame does its thing and returns a value to the previous frame that called it. Think of it as an un-stacking of frames.Hope thats a little more clear in terms of what you mentioned., Resolved,0
Friday September 13th 2013 3:44 am -04:00,I wouldnt get too hung up on the jargon. Its very much common sense.Think of a stack of books. Thats all it is. One book on top of another. Or as Professor Gries mentioned in one of his videos its like a stack of plates but upside down. The upside down reference is because a frame gets created and instead of being put on top its put below.A frame itself isnt too complicated. We all have frames at home you know like a picture frame with four sides that looks like a box. Thats why they call it a frame. Except in this instance a frame is a so-called global frame with its function definitions and other frames that get stacked as functions get called. No matter the frames are still four-sided boxes that represent function calls. Thats why they call it a call stack. Function calls stacked on top of each other.We could try and make it more complicated but then it would probably be for a cocktail party or something. :), Resolved,1
