Monday September 16th 2013 5:34 pm -04:00,The string module still exists but most of the functions that once existed in earlier versions of Python have now been turned into string methods instead. Heres one function that still exists though inside the string module and is actually kind of handy:  >>> import string>>> text =   lEaRn tO    proGram >>> string.capwords(text)Learn To Program  In terms of functionality there are several reasons why some functions are in a modules and why some functions are methods instead and live in a class. The issue of memory has already been mentioned above but heres a few more...First it doesnt always make sense to create methods for everything. Youd be writing a lot of duplicate code for nothing. For example take the len() function. Why is there no string method that gives us the length of a string i.e. my_string.len(). The answer is because having one generic function that calculates the length of a string can also be used for other types as well. Like lists for example. One function many applications.Second theres the historical legacy aspect. No doubt it took awhile to turn string functions into string methods. I can imagine that a lot of existing code uses the square root function for example. We could probably create a square root method that is tied directly to a number when its created. Something like the following but theres probably no need:  >>> 144.sqrt()12.0  No doubt there many other reasons but I hope this is somewhat useful in explaining the differences., Resolved,1
Friday October 4th 2013 9:16 pm -04:00,You are correct that there is a string method to get length. But the so-called special or magic methods are not always equivalent to their function counterparts.Some functions have added functionality compared to their special methods. Functionality such as checking for errors or the ability to handle exceptions. Theres also the issue of future changes to the underlying code which may cause a program to break if someone is not using the proper method or function to begin with.For example s.__next__() is not equivalent to next(s):   >>> s = iter(a)>>> s.__next__()a>>> s.__next__()Traceback (most recent call last):  File <pyshell#71> line 1 in <module>    s.__next__()StopIteration>>> s = iter(a)>>> next(s)a>>> next(s)Traceback (most recent call last):  File <pyshell#74> line 1 in <module>    next(s)StopIteration  In the above code both of them broke as expected. Below its different in that the function can handle the exception simply because it has added functionality:>>> s = iter(a)>>> s.__next__()Traceback (most recent call last):  File <pyshell#76> line 1 in <module>    s.__next__()TypeError: expected 0 arguments got 1>>> s = iter(a)>>> next(s )a>>> next(s )  , Resolved,0
