Thursday September 12th 2013 6:24 pm -04:00,Checking the length of a postal code is definitely a good idea. But from I understand the UK postal codes can be anywhere from 5-8 characters in length?Theres also a third option which is a little more complicated and involves the use of regular expressions. Not sure if youve heard of regular expressions before? But theyre used to make sure postal codes phone numbers etc. are all valid. For example heres some code that checks whether a string is a valid UK postal code: >>> import re>>> post_code_1 = AA11 1AA>>> post_code_2 = AA111AA>>> print(re.findall(r[A-Z]{12}[0-9R][0-9A-Z]? [0-9][A-Z]{2} post_code_1))[AA11 1AA]>>> print(re.findall(r[A-Z]{12}[0-9R][0-9A-Z]? [0-9][A-Z]{2} post_code_2))>>> re.findall(r[A-Z]{12}[0-9R][0-9A-Z]? [0-9][A-Z]{2} post_code_1) != True>>> re.findall(r[A-Z]{12}[0-9R][0-9A-Z]? [0-9][A-Z]{2} post_code_2) != False  Basically regular expressions check to see if a string is in a certain format. In the above code if the postal code is valid then it gets put into a list. If the postal code is not valid then the list is empty. Which means you can check if the list is empty or not i.e. True or False. And in the above example we know postal_code_2 is not valid because the list is empty.The format of the regular expression above is one that I Googled so Im not even sure if its 100% valid in terms of UK postal codes. But there are regular expressions out there for just about everything including credit card numbers email addresses etc.So regular expressions are just another option to think about if you want to test for validity.Edit: Reference the regular expression method Im sure theres a better one than findall since that one is more for finding a particular string in a much larger string such as a text file. But the idea is still the same.,None,0
