Sunday September 15th 2013 12:43 pm -04:00,Everything you need to know about how floating point numbers work in Python can be found in this document:   http://docs.python.org/3.3/tutorial/floatingpoint.html Its a bit long and complicated for people who arent familiar with how things work but I can explain some of the stuff and summarize the important parts. First there are two very important things when it comes to floating point numbers. Theres the actual number and then theres the representation of the number. Some programmers even call the representation an illusion. :) Second in Python floating point numbers can either be represented by 17 significant digits or a shortened version. For example 0.10000000000000001 or 0.1. Significant digits include all digits both to the left and the right of the decimal point except if the left digit is zero. So using your example of 7 / 3 and 2.3333333333333335 youll notice that it has 17 significant digits. Which is 1 to the left of the decimal point and 16 to the right. Thats how Python displays a floating point number. But this number is a representation and NOT the actual number. In the next post having covered the basics Ill show you how to see the actual number and why its a 5... ,None,3
Sunday September 15th 2013 1:02 pm -04:00,Heres the different ways of representing 7 / 3...  >>> 7 / 32.3333333333333335>>> format(7 / 3 .17g)2.3333333333333335>>> format(7 / 3 .16f)2.3333333333333335  First example was already explained above. Second example is how to format with 17 significant digits. Notice the g after 17. Third example is how to format with 16 digits to the right of the decimal point. Notice the f after 16. Whats importantto note is these are representations and NOT the actual number. And that they all do the same thing.Now the exciting part. Have you figured out how to see the actual number? Yes thats right just expand the number of digits to the right of the decimal point and voila! :)  >>> format(7 / 3 .60f)2.333333333333333481363069950020872056484222412109375000000000  Notice something really interesting? What the heck is 481363... doing after a bunch of threes? Thats where the five is coming from since its rounding up from 481363....In the next post Ill explain how the actual number gets generated. ,None,2
Sunday September 15th 2013 2:20 pm -04:00,For people interested in the actual number and how it gets created theres a couple of things to know. And all of this can be found in the link above. Highly recommend you bookmark that Python web page for future reference. First as Nick mentioned all numbers cant be represented by 1s and 0s. So theres this standard that has been developed over the years to approximate certain numbers. The standard is known as IEEE 754 with the latest version being IEEE 754-2008. And this standard is pretty much in all computers:   http://grouper.ieee.org/groups/754/ http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/xpl/articleDetails.jsp?arnumber=4610935   Second theres the easy way to calculate floats and the actual number. And then theres the hard way which is more step by step using formulas. Easy way is to use existing functions. Floats are just two integers divided by themselves so you can use the decimal or fractions modules. Heres several examples in terms of how to find the two integers that created the float for 7 / 3:    >>> from decimal import Decimal>>> from fractions import Fraction>>> >>> Fraction.from_float(2.3333333333333335)Fraction(5254199565265579 2251799813685248)>>> 5254199565265579 / 22517998136852482.3333333333333335>>> format(5254199565265579 / 2251799813685248 .60f)2.333333333333333481363069950020872056484222412109375000000000>>> format(5254199565265579 / 2 ** 51 .60f)2.333333333333333481363069950020872056484222412109375000000000>>> 2251799813685248 == 2 ** 51True>>> >>> (2.3333333333333335).as_integer_ratio()(5254199565265579 2251799813685248)>>> Decimal.from_float(2.3333333333333335)Decimal(2.333333333333333481363069950020872056484222412109375)>>> format(Decimal.from_float(2.3333333333333335) .17)2.3333333333333335>>> format(Decimal.from_float(2.3333333333333335) .53)2.333333333333333481363069950020872056484222412109375   Definitely no lack of functions.Hope this was a good summary. If anyone is interested in doing it the hard way which is more step by step using formulas then let me know. The Python document shows you how to do it for 0.1 but 7 / 3 is slightly harder. Nice little challenge. :),None,1
