Monday September 16th 2013 2:24 am -04:00,Sometimes there are subtle differences between a right and a wrong answer. And it doesnt take very much for it to be marked incorrectly i.e. you added an extra space left out a parentheses etc.But theres one thing you can do since you have both a correct answer and an incorrect answer. And that is to compare the two strings. For example:  >>> test5 = your_function(another_function(argument1 argument2))>>> test7 = your_function(another_function(argument1 argument2))>>> test5 == test7True  Now that will tell you right away if your answers are indeed both the same.Next if they are the same then the next step would be to check the actual questions. As you re-attempt certain exercises the questions may change. Theres a built-in mechanism to randomly produce new questions and even change the answers on different attempts. I dont think thats the case for this particular question though. It seems to remain the same but its always a good idea to check beforehand.Hope the idea of comparing strings helped out., Resolved,0
