Tuesday September 17th 2013 1:20 pm -04:00,Technically everything in Python is an object. It all depends in terms of how deep you want to go into the code. But even modules themselves are objects. For example:  >>> import math>>> math<module math (built-in)>>>> type(math)<class module>>>> id(math)52724488>>> import random>>> random<module random from C:\\Python33\\lib\\random.py>>>> type(random)<class module>>>> id(random)52690440  So Python searched for the module when you I used import. Found it created an instance of the module class i.e. an object and assigned a variable i.e. math to point to the address of the object in memory i.e. the id().In terms of the syntax i.e. abc.xyz its just a hierarchy of left to right. We could easily have abc.def.ghi.jkl.xyz as well. But abc is an object so is def etc. For example:  >>> import builtins>>> builtins.len.__class__.__class__.__class__<class type>  And as Stijn mentioned above if you leave off the parentheses then youre just getting information i.e. the attribute of the object. When you uses parentheses then youre obviously executing a method or function call. For example:  >>> str.find<method find of str objects>>>> id(abc)35321816>>> hex(35321816)0x21af7d8>>> abc.find<built-in method find of str object at 0x000000000213F7D8>>>> type(abc.find)<class builtin_function_or_method>>>> abc.find(c)2, Unresolved,1
Tuesday September 17th 2013 1:59 pm -04:00,In terms of the len() function its kind of special because its a built-in function. Which means that the actual function is written in the C programming language. So in order to work with a C function we need some sort of middleman. And that middleman is something called a wrapper...A built-in function object is a wrapper around a C function. Examples of built-in functions are len() and math.sin() (math is a standard built-in module). The number and type of the arguments are determined by the C function.http://docs.python.org/3.3/reference/datamodel.htmlThere are different types of wrappers in order to interface with the underlying language. Technical terms but theres method wrappers slot wrappers and so on. The built-in types like int str and list use slot wrappers:  >>> abc.__len__<method-wrapper __len__ of str object at 0x000000000213F7D8>>>> type(abc.__len__)<class method-wrapper>>>> str.__len__<slot wrapper __len__ of str objects>>>> type(str.__len__)<class wrapper_descriptor>   Now if youre not totally confused this is the easy part...Not all objects require their own methods. Think of abc.len() in terms of string methods. Doesnt exist because then we would need one for lists tuples and dictionaries as well. Much better to use a single generic C function with a wrapper on top. For now anyways. :)  , Unresolved,1
Wednesday September 18th 2013 2:15 am -04:00,Anonymous this is how basic object-oriented programming works (OOP). Will try and make it as simple as possible.Class is like a blueprint. It contains all the information in terms of how to build an Object. Just like the blueprint for a house.Objects are instances of the Class. Just one Class but many Objects that are all built the same way. Exactly like a house one blueprint but a whole bunch of houses that look the same way.Methods are the way we interact with Objects. If I want to change a string to uppercase then I need some sort of way or Method to do that.Now you know OOP. :)The concept of Objects in programming is exactly like the real world., Unresolved,1
