uffle. Which is definitely much more interesting than the shuffle method thats for sure.  ,None,0
Monday September 23rd 2013 5:02 am -04:00,Evelyn I understand what youre saying... But random is random.It doesnt matter whether you choose to shuffle the cards in a so-called fixed list for example and to then choose the first card. Or have a fixed list and randomly choose an index number from 1 to 52. Its the exact same thing. In fact the shuffle method actually calls random within the random module to shuffle the cards. Theres no difference.Now obviously using the pop method is totally different. If you remove a card from the deck then theres absolutely no chance whatsoever that it can be selected again. Only way for that particular card to be selected again would be to reconstitute the deck.In terms of the shaman thats so easy to do. Theres a bag with 27 stones each stone has a face and a back i.e. 54 possible definitions. Those are like the properties. Theyre like upside down or right-side up. You simply create a list which represents the bag. Each stone is an object in that bag and you can either shuffle them or leave them as is to then select randomly.In fact once the stones are an object theres no limit. Simply create an object to represent the mound and pop the stones from the bag onto the mound. From there its just a matter of writing if statements to see how the stones ended up i.e. did they stack on top of each other did they group together are they alone or whatever.Rinse and repeat very easy to do. :)  ,None,0
