Friday September 27th 2013 6:19 am -04:00,What happens to those old memory locations depends on a number of things. Usually it has to do with the type of object thats in the memory location. And how a particular program is written as well.Python uses a two-step process to handle memory allocation. It uses what is known as reference counting and garbage collection.Reference counting is easy enough to understand. Take a list for example. The list object itself will count the number of references that are pointing to it. If the count is zero then itll be freed. The problem with reference counting is that sometimes it gets messed up. For example think of a list that references itself where the count can never be zero. This problem is known as reference cycles.So this is where the garbage collector makes its appearance. Its purpose is really to deal with reference cycles. And it does this on a scheduled basis every now and then where it looks to get rid of various objects and to free up memory.Garbage collection itself is handled by the gc module i.e. you can import gc and call help. Objects are considered as 1st 2nd or 3rd generation. More specifically 0 1 and 2. New objects are 1st generation and if they survive the first sweep of a garbage collection then theyre moved to the 2nd generation and so on.Garbage collection though has a certain threshold before its run. If you type the following code youll see it:  >>> import gc>>> gc.get_threshold()(700 10 10)  The way the threshold works is based on object allocations and deallocations. So if theres 700 more allocations than deallocations then the garbage collector will run.Garbage collection as a subject can be quite complicated but heres a few links with much more info:  http://docs.python.org/3.3/library/gc.htmlhttp://www.digi.com/wiki/developer/index.php/Python_Garbage_Collectionhttp://svn.python.org/view/python/trunk/Modules/gcmodule.c?revision=81029&view=markupEdit: For those interested heres a more updated version of the C module (26 Sep 2013):  http://hg.python.org/cpython/file/tip/Modules/gcmodule.c   , Unresolved,3
Friday September 27th 2013 7:40 am -04:00,For those interested heres an example:  >>> import gc>>> gc.get_threshold()(700 10 10)  You can see the threshold for the three generations i.e. its 700 for new objects. So what we can do is create a list object that references itself. This will mess up its reference counting since it can never become zero. Which will then cause it to be a prime candidate for the garbage collector.  >>> def make_reference_cycle():    lst = [ ]    lst.append(lst)>>> gc.get_count()(137 10 2)  Notice the function above creates a list which references itself. The get_count() method shows us the three generations. So all we have to do is call that function over and over to push the new objects above 700...  >>> for x in range(600):	make_reference_cycle()>>> gc.get_count()(0 11 2)  Notice how the garbage collector kicked in. No more 1st generation objects to clean up. One object actually survived and was moved to the 2nd generation. Lets keep going...  >>> for x in range(600):	make_reference_cycle()>>> gc.get_count()(550 11 2)>>> for x in range(600):	make_reference_cycle()>>> gc.get_count()(369 0 3)  Notice the 3rd generation? Interesting how there always seems to be at least one object that survives.Garbage collection in action. :)  , Unresolved,2
