Saturday October 5th 2013 9:06 am -04:00,The .readlines() and .read() methods are part of the io module:  http://docs.python.org/3.3/library/io.htmlThe io module is a bit complicated since a lot of methods are inherited from base classes that are higher up in the hierarchy. And these inherited methods may actually be overridden in the current class as well.So you could do this by starting at the top and try to find what youre looking for:  >>> import io>>> help(io)At the top of the I/O hierarchy is the abstract base class IOBase...  Or you could check out what sort of object you created by starting at the bottom:  >>> file = open(temp.txt r)>>> file<_io.TextIOWrapper name=temp.txt mode=r encoding=cp1252>>>> help(io.TextIOWrapper)Help on class TextIOWrapper in module io...>>> help(io.TextIOWrapper.readlines)Help on method_descriptor:readlines(...)    Return a list of lines from the stream...  If you read the help on TextIOWrapper youll notice that the method resolution order goes from TextIOWrapper to TextIOBase to IOBase and finally to builtins.object at the top.And that the method .readlines() is inherited from IOBase. So you could do this as well:  >>> help(io.IOBase.readlines)Help on method_descriptor:readlines(...)    Return a list of lines from the stream.        hint can be specified to control the number of lines read: no more    lines will be read if the total size (in bytes/characters) of all    lines so far exceeds hint.  Hope that helps somewhat.  , Unresolved,1
