Wednesday October 2nd 2013 8:48 am -04:00,Saying Python is not fast because its an interpreted language is kind of a misnomer. Usually theres very little code that actually gets interpreted since Python is more like the glue which holds or binds everything together as is so often mentioned but never really understood.Its like a high-level language which sits on top of other low-level languages such as C for example. So yes itll be slow if you use a for loop that counts a string of a million characters. But thats not the way someone should be using Python and the very reason as to why all these pre-compiled built-in functions exist.Also theres quite a lot of Python code thats out there in the so-called professional market and which is used in real-time but that we dont see simply because its hidden or in some sort of backend. This is often the case for places like Google Dropbox and so on.As an example theres a professor on Coursera that teaches quantitative analysis and his firm uses Python at the very backend like all the way at the backend to do portfolio management optimization time series analysis event analysis and so on. But you dont see it because its coupled with various other software and everything communicates through JSON objects. So someone using the actual software just sees an HTML5 frontend and has no clue that theres even any Python being used.  ,None,0
