Wednesday October 2nd 2013 9:12 pm -04:00,Judi very nice find.Are you sure this is your first exposure to programming? I dont even think that experienced programmers would have spotted that one LOL. :)There does seem to be an error in the book if you ask me. Seems to me that theyre making the assumption that the shorthand version for assigning variables is the same as the regular assignment version but its not. For example: appointments = appointments + [16:30]appointments += [16:30]  So what ends up happening with a regular assignment is that a new object gets created as expected. But with the shorthand version its different in that the existing object gets modified instead.Heres some code in the Visualizer to see the difference in action. Also notice Im printing out the ID and that there is indeed a new list for the first one. But with the shorthand version it simply gets modified i.e. just like the append method:  Code in Python Visualizer And heres some documentation that explains the difference between the two: http://docs.python.org/3.3/reference/simple_stmts.html#augmented-assignment-statementsAn augmented assignment expression like x += 1 can be rewritten as x = x + 1 to achieve a similar but not exactly equal effect. In the augmented version x is only evaluated once. Also when possible the actual operation is performed in-place meaning that rather than creating a new object and assigning that to the target the old object is modified instead.  , Unresolved,1
