Thursday October 3rd 2013 2:56 am -04:00,To answer your question Python doesnt know that you are doing a for loop over the index as opposed to just a normal for loop. It doesnt even know when youre doing a normal for loop either. The only thing that Python knows is that its doing a loop and thats it. So when you think about it its really up to us to structure the loop so that it produces what we need. Heres an example...The moment Python sees the for statement it knows that its suppose to go into a loop. And thats the only thing it knows. What next? Well Python knows that it has to grab the first thing thats inside whateverfollows the in keyword such as:    for thing in team:     # which could also be written as...for thing in [Dave Bob Joe Mike]:  So we get thing = Dave thing = Bob thing = Joe etc. as the loop keeps going around. Now to create a loop thats going to be used for indices what do we need? Is s[Dave] going to work or how about s[Mike]. No none of those will work. They dont even make any sense. Obviously what we needis a bunch of numbers. Ideally numbers that go from 0-9 1-5 or whatever. And it would look something like this instead:    for thing in [0 1 2 3 4]:     # which could also be written as...for thing in range(5):   So we now get thing = 0 thing = 1 thing = 3 etc. Much better!Which is like saying s[thing] or s[0] s[1] s[2] etc. Notice any real difference between the two loops? Thats right there is no difference except for the fact that if were going to be working with indices then we need numbers.Hope this put you back on track.  , Resolved,3
